<div class="page" id="page-blueprint" style="display:none!important">
  <div class="section-head">
    <h2>Full System Blueprint</h2>
    <p>Technical architecture, data methodology, model design, and implementation roadmap for the WYDOT Turnover Prediction & Retention Decision Support System.</p>
  </div>

  <div style="max-width:900px">

  <!-- Executive Summary -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title" style="font-size:18px"><div class="icon" style="background:#e8f0fe">📋</div> Executive Summary</div>
    <p style="color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.8;font-size:14px">
      The WYDOT Turnover Prediction & Retention Decision Support System is a machine-learning–powered HR tool that ingests employee pulse survey data and produces three outputs per employee: (1) a <strong>turnover risk probability</strong> from a logistic regression model trained on 607 WYDOT records, (2) a <strong>theme-level diagnostic</strong> across 8 HR domains, and (3) <strong>evidence-based retention strategy recommendations</strong> mapped from national DOT HR research.
      <br><br>
      The MVP is built as a single self-contained HTML application using pure JavaScript with SHAP-analogous linear weight attribution. The production version is designed as a FastAPI + React + PostgreSQL system with a Claude-powered chatbot. Both versions support individual employee analysis and batch Excel upload workflows.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- A. Problem Framing -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title" style="font-size:18px"><div class="icon" style="background:#fdf0f0">A</div> Problem Framing</div>
    <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);margin:0 0 10px">Business Problem</h3>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:16px">WYDOT faces workforce turnover that is costly, operationally disruptive, and concentrated in specific themes (pay competitiveness, supervisor relationships, career growth). HR lacks a systematic, data-driven tool to identify at-risk employees early and prescribe targeted interventions before employees decide to leave.</p>

    <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);margin:0 0 10px">ML Problem Definition</h3>
    <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.8">
      <strong>Layer 1 — Binary Classification:</strong> Given 32 survey responses, predict P(leave) vs P(stay). Target variable: <code>left=1</code> (exit survey records), <code>left=0</code> (stayer records).<br>
      <strong>Layer 2 — Theme Attribution:</strong> Compute grouped theme scores; identify which theme has the lowest average score (= most concerning domain for that employee).<br>
      <strong>Layer 3 — Strategy Recommendation:</strong> Rule-based mapping from identified risk theme → ranked retention strategies from national DOT survey, filtered by effectiveness score.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- B. Data Architecture -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title" style="font-size:18px"><div class="icon" style="background:#f4f0fd">B</div> Data Architecture &amp; Integration</div>

    <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);margin:0 0 10px">Dataset Integration</h3>
    <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:16px">
      <strong>Exit Survey (n=307):</strong> 32 Likert-scale survey items + <code>Turnover_Type_Final</code> + <code>Whatareyourreasonsforleavingwydot</code>. Label: <code>left=1</code>. Note: <code>Turnover_Type_Final</code> and <code>Whatareyourreasonsforleavingwydot</code> are excluded from features (data leakage).<br><br>
      <strong>Stayer Dataset (n=300):</strong> Same 32 survey items + <code>Employment_Status</code> column (confirm active). <code>Whatareyourreasonsforleavingwydot</code> is simulated/null for stayers. Label: <code>left=0</code>.<br><br>
      <strong>Combined Dataset (n=607):</strong> Vertically concatenate both; align on shared 32 feature columns; add binary label column. Near-balanced dataset (51% leavers / 49% stayers) — minimal class imbalance concern.<br><br>
      <strong>National DOT Survey:</strong> Used exclusively as strategy knowledge base. Not used as ML training data. Maps themes to retention strategies with effectiveness scores (1–4 Likert mean across 31 DOTs).
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);margin:0 0 10px">Feature Engineering — 8 Theme Groups</h3>
    <div style="overflow-x:auto">
      <table class="data-table" style="font-size:12px">
        <thead><tr><th>Theme</th><th>Survey Items Included</th><th>Score Calculation</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Compensation &amp; Career</strong></td><td>Pay, Career development, PMI review, Recognition</td><td>Mean of 4 items</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Supervisor / Leadership</strong></td><td>Supervisor feedback, free to suggest, comfort with supervisor, complaint resolution, sensitive, communication, receptive</td><td>Mean of 7 items</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Training &amp; Development</strong></td><td>Personal job training, training programs, proper training to perform job</td><td>Mean of 3 items</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Work Culture &amp; Team</strong></td><td>Cooperation within dept, cooperation with other depts, team worked well, treated as valuable member</td><td>Mean of 4 items</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Working Conditions</strong></td><td>Equipment/resources/facilities, physical conditions, job duties clarity, get resources</td><td>Mean of 4 items</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Safety</strong></td><td>Safety culture, supervisor safety environment</td><td>Mean of 2 items</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Job Security</strong></td><td>Job security feeling</td><td>Single item</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Communication / HR</strong></td><td>Informed of policies, comfort with HR, supervisor policy compliance, fairness/equal treatment, teamwork development, resolve problems</td><td>Mean of 6 items</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);margin:16px 0 10px">Missing Value Handling</h3>
    <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.8">
      Impute missing Likert items with the <strong>column median</strong> from the training set (robust to outliers, preserves scale range). For stayer records where some items were not collected, impute with the stayer group median for that item. Flag employees with >30% missing items and exclude from batch predictions with a warning.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- C. Model Design -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title" style="font-size:18px"><div class="icon" style="background:#f0fafb">C</div> Model Design &amp; Recommendation</div>

    <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);margin:0 0 10px">Recommended Model: Logistic Regression</h3>
    <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:14px">
      For HR-facing Likert survey data with n=607, <strong>Logistic Regression is the optimal choice</strong> because: (1) coefficients are directly interpretable as feature weights — HR can understand why a prediction was made; (2) it performs extremely well on linearly-separable survey data; (3) it produces calibrated probabilities; (4) it is fast and deployable without complex infrastructure; (5) SHAP values for LR are simply the feature contribution = coefficient × feature value, giving immediate explainability.
    </div>

    <div style="overflow-x:auto;margin-bottom:16px">
      <table class="data-table" style="font-size:12px">
        <thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>Best For</th><th>HR Explainability</th><th>Recommended?</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Logistic Regression</strong></td><td>Balanced Likert survey data, small-medium n</td><td>⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ Direct coefficients</td><td>✅ Primary choice</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Random Forest</td><td>Non-linear patterns, mixed data types</td><td>⭐⭐⭐ Feature importance</td><td>✅ Secondary/ensemble</td></tr>
          <tr><td>XGBoost</td><td>Large n, complex interactions</td><td>⭐⭐⭐ SHAP values needed</td><td>⚠️ Overkill for n=607</td></tr>
          <tr><td>SVM</td><td>High-dimensional, text features</td><td>⭐⭐ Hard to explain</td><td>❌ Not recommended</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:15px;font-weight:700;color:var(--ink);margin:0 0 10px">Evaluation Strategy</h3>
    <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.8">
      Use <strong>stratified 5-fold cross-validation</strong>. Primary metric: <strong>AUC-ROC</strong> (measures discriminative ability across all thresholds). Secondary metrics: Precision/Recall at threshold=0.5, F1-score. Accept model if AUC-ROC ≥ 0.75. For HR use, <strong>Recall is more important than Precision</strong> — missing a high-risk employee (false negative) is more costly than over-flagging (false positive). Set classification threshold at 0.40 instead of 0.50 to increase recall.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- D. Strategy Knowledge Base -->
  <div class="card">
    <div class="card-title" style="font-size:18px"><div class="icon" style="background:#f0faf5">D</div> Strategy Knowledge Base &amp; Recommendation Engine</div>

