    <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink2);line-height:1.9">
      <strong>Current Limitations:</strong><br>
      • <em>Survey response bias:</em> Exit survey respondents may underreport supervisor issues or overreport pay concerns due to social desirability. Stayer data may also be biased (employees who are very dissatisfied may not complete surveys).<br>
      • <em>No temporal data:</em> The model treats each employee as a static snapshot; it cannot model how satisfaction changes over time (tenure, seasonal patterns).<br>
      • <em>No demographic features:</em> Age, tenure, job classification, district are not included — adding them could significantly improve prediction accuracy but requires careful fairness analysis.<br>
      • <em>n=607 is modest:</em> The model will generalize well for the current data but may need retraining as WYDOT surveys more employees.<br><br>
      <strong>Future Improvements:</strong><br>
      • Add employee tenure and job classification as features (with fairness audit)<br>
      • Implement survival analysis (time-to-turnover prediction)<br>
      • Build automatic model retraining pipeline (retrain quarterly with new survey data)<br>
      • Add real-time pulse survey integration (rather than manual file upload)<br>
      • Implement differential fairness analysis across protected groups<br>
      • Expand chatbot to retrieve specific employee records from the database<br>
      • Add peer-comparison benchmarking ("this employee's scores vs district average")
